Calculation and interpretation of physiological indices derived from tree ring d13C

Isotope Dendrochronology
COURSE: DISC, LTRR, UNIVERSITY OF ARIZONA. INSTRUCTORS: S. BELMECHERI & P. SZEJNER

Instructions

The following code and comments should further your experience using tree ring and atmospheric d13C data to calculate WUE and other physiological indices. This exercise relies upon raw tree-ring d13C measurements, atmospheric d13C measurements and uses the photosynthesis biochemical model of Farqhuar 1982.

There are a few questions throughout to catalyze understanding and critical thinking. The analysis is broken into four main parts (including 20 questions). At the end, you should have gone through many of the steps commonly used for reconstructing and interpreting iWUE derived from tree ring d13C. You will also be familiar with uncertainties related to such calculations and best practices to perform them.

You will need to download the R project from https://github.com/SBelmecheri/DISCO-Ntebook3.git and set your own working directory. Once you open the Notebook 3.Rproj in R studio you can open the Notebook3.Rmd file to proceed with the exercise.

PART 0: Setting up directories and files

You will need the three following files in one directory:

  1. Tree-ring d13C measurements. The filename is "LIL.txt"

  2. Atmospheric 13C and [CO2] data. The filename is"ATM.txt"

  3. Regional temperature data. The filename is "CRU_TT.txt"

You will also need to install and load the dplR and rpmodel packages:

```r
library(dplR)
library(rpmodel)

Question 1: Compare both trends. Describe and interpret the relationship between the decline in d13C and the increase in CO2 concentration. 

## PART 2: Calculating iWUE- SIMPLE APPROACH 

The Farquhar, O'Leary, and Berry 1982 biochemical model describes the isotopic discrimination against 13C (13C) during carbon diffusion and fixation by plants. The Farquhar et al. equation can be written as follows:

13C = a+(b-a)*(ci/ca)

where:  

a=4.4 is the fractionation due to CO2 diffusion in air through the stomata.

b= 28 is the apparent net fractionation by RuBisCO during carboxylation.

ci and ca are are the leaf intercellular and ambient partial pressure of CO2 (Pa), respectively.

From the equation above, ci can be calculated as follows:

ci =  ca*(13C-a)/(b-a)

We know `ca` from measurements. `ca` is in ppm. You can use `ca` in ppm such as:

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuIyBXZSBrbm93IGNhIGZyb20gbWVhc3VyZW1lbnRzLmNhIGlzIGluIHBwbS4geW91IHVzZSB1c2UgaXQgYXMgaXMgXG5jYSA8LSBBVE0uQ08yICMgaW4gcHBtXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
# We know ca from measurements.ca is in ppm. you use use it as is 
ca <- ATM.CO2 # in ppm

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->

Or use `ca` in Pa as follows:

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuIyB5b3UgbmVlZCAgciBwYWNrYWdlIFxccnBtb2RlbFxcXG5saWJyYXJ5KFxccnBtb2RlbFxcKVxuYGBgXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r

and the function `calc_patm {rpmodel}` to calculate atmospheric pressure at sea level. The variable needed is elevation.

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuZWx2PSAxNjAwICMgRWxldmF0aW9uIGFib3ZlIHNlYS1sZXZlbCAobS5hLnMubC4pXG5wYXRtPC0gY2FsY19wYXRtKGVsdiwgcGF0bTAgPSAxMDEzMjUpXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
elv= 1600 # Elevation above sea-level (m.a.s.l.)
patm<- calc_patm(elv, patm0 = 101325)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->

calculate `ca` as follows:

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuY2EgPC0gKCAxLmUtNiApICogY2EgKiBwYXRtICAjIGluIFBhXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
ca <- ( 1.e-6 ) * ca * patm  # in Pa

13C (`d13C.disc`) can then be calculated as follows:

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuZDEzQy5kaXNjIDwtIChBVE0uMTNDLVRSMTMpLygxK1RSMTMvMTAwMClcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
```r
d13C.disc <- (ATM.13C-TR13)/(1+TR13/1000)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->

And `ci` as follows:

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuYT00LjRcbmI9MjhcbmNpIDwtICBjYSooZDEzQy5kaXNjLWEpLyhiLWEpXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
a=4.4
b=28
ci <-  ca*(d13C.disc-a)/(b-a)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->

```r
iwue <- (ca-ci)/1.6

Question 2: describe the trends of the various physiological indices.

Question 3: based on what you have learned in the Isotope theory lectures, describe the tree's physiological response over time at this site.

## PART 3: Calculating iWUE- COMPREHENSIVE APPROACH 

In the Farquhar et al. model, the d13C is the isotopic ratio for sugars fixed in the leaf. For tree-ring cellulose, a correction factor accounts for the offset of d13C between leaf sugars and tree-ring cellulose. The offset results from post-photosynthetic fractionation processes (Gessler et al., 2014). 

The offset between whole wood and leaves is ~1.3  0.2 for oak and conifer species. Additional isotopic offsets include the difference between tree-ring cellulose and bulk wood with an average value of ~1.3  0.2, and isotopic depletion between primary assimilates and bulk leaf with values of -0.5  1. 

Upscaling d13C measurements from tree rings to the leaf level can significantly improve estimates of 13C and reduce uncertainties (offsets) in determining the ratio of ci to ca.

We can scale tree ring d13 to leaf level using a factor `d`.

`d` represents the sum of post-photosynthetic isotope fractionations between the organic leaf matter and the plant material considered. Choose the d value based on the studied material (for this site, it is cellulose)


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuZD0xLjkgIyBmb3IgZDEzQyBtZWFzdXJlZCBpbiB3b29kXG5kPTIuMSAjIGZvciBkMTNDIG1lYXN1cmVkIGluIGNlbGx1bG9zZVxuYGBgXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
```r
d=1.9 # for d13C measured in wood
d=2.1 # for d13C measured in cellulose

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


This correction can be made as follows: * Choose the appropriate d factor for this site

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuZDEzQy5kaXNjLmxlYWYgPC0gKEFUTS4xM0MtKFRSMTMtZCkpLygxKyhUUjEzLWQpLzEwMDApXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
d13C.disc.leaf <- (ATM.13C-(TR13-d))/(1+(TR13-d)/1000)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


Leaf level ci `ci.leaf` can be calculated as follows:

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuY2kubGVhZiA8LSAgY2EqKGQxM0MuZGlzYy5sZWFmLWEpLyhiLWEpXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
ci.leaf <-  ca*(d13C.disc.leaf-a)/(b-a)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


Leaf level intrinsic water use efficiency  `iwue.leaf` can be calculated as follows:

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuaXd1ZS5sZWFmIDwtIChjYS1jaS5sZWFmKS8xLjZcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
```r
iwue.leaf <- (ca-ci.leaf)/1.6

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->

layout(matrix(1:6,nrow = 3, ncol = 2,byrow = F), widths = c(4,4),heights = c(2,2,2),respect = TRUE)
par(mar=c(4,5,2,0.1))

plot(d13C.disc,ylab=\D13C (permil.VPDB)\,xlab=\Years\, main=\\, ylim=c(range(c(d13C.disc.leaf,d13C.disc))))
        lines(d13C.disc.leaf, col=\#0B775E\, )
plot(ca,ylab=\CO2 (ppm)\,xlab=\Years\, main=\\)
plot(ci,ylab=\ci (pa)\,xlab=\Years\, main=\FARQUHAR-MODEL\,ylim=c(range(c(ci, ci.leaf))))
        lines(ci.leaf, col=\#0B775E\)
plot(iwue,ylab=\ iwue (umol/mol)\,xlab=\Years\, main=\\,ylim=c(range(c(iwue, iwue.leaf))))
        lines(iwue.leaf, col=\#0B775E\)
plot(ci/ca,ylab=\ci/ca\,xlab=\Years\, main=\\, ylim=c(range(c(ci/ca, ci.leaf/ca))))
        lines(ci.leaf/ca, col=\#0B775E\)

Question 4: what differences do you observe between physiological indices at stem level and leaf level?


The version of the Farquhar model we used above is a simplified description of the isotopic discrimination. It does not include the fractionation effects during the transfer of CO2 from substomatal cavities to the site of fixation via the mesophyll, and during mitochondrial respiration and photorespiration. While the mesophyll fractionation and their values remain highly unconstrained, recent studies have recommended the inclusion of the photorespiratory effect in the discrimination model as this term contributes to an increase of 13C with ca rise by 0.004 ppm-1 (Keeling et al., 2017; Lavergne et al., 2019).


A Farquhar model that includes the photorespiratory term is as follows:

13C = a+(b-a)*(ci/ca) -f*(Gst/ca)

The photorespiratory term is the: f*(Gst/ca)

The fractionation due to photorespiration, f, is 12 permil. 

Gst (or *, Gamma Star) is the CO2 compensation point in the absence of mitochondrial respiration (Pa), it is calculated from the temperature (T) and atmospheric pressure response.You can use the calc_gammastar(tc, patm) function from the rpmodel to calculate Gamma Star



Based on `Notebook 1` and the temperature file, define the appropriate temperature window (e.g.average growing season). This has to be a Time series of site level temperature variability during the summer or growing season or relevant season for trees at this site. Below is an example for summer (June-July-August):

```r
gridded.tt.data <- ts(read.table(\CRU_TT.txt\,header=T),start=1901,frequency=1)
tt.JJA <- rowMeans(gridded.tt.data[,c(6,7,8)])
tt.JJA <- ts(tt.JJA ,start=1901,frequency =1)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


Calculate gamma star `Gst` as follows:

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxudGMgPC0gdHQuSkpBICMgYW5kIHBhdG0gaGFzIGJlZW4gZGVmaW5lZCBlYXJsaWVyLlxuR3N0IDwtIGNhbGNfZ2FtbWFzdGFyKHRjLCBwYXRtKVxuYGBgXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
```r
tc <- tt.JJA # and patm has been defined earlier.
Gst <- calc_gammastar(tc, patm)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


And the photorespiratory term `photoresp_term` as follows:

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuZj0xMiAjVGhlIGZyYWN0aW9uYXRpb24gZHVlIHRvIHBob3RvcmVzcGlyYXRpb25cbnBob3RvcmVzcF90ZXJtIDwtIGYqKEdzdC9jYSkgIyBjYSBpcyAgaW4gUGFcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
```r
f=12 #The fractionation due to photorespiration
photoresp_term <- f*(Gst/ca) # ca is  in Pa

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->

Calculate ci to include photorespiration:

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuY2kubGVhZi5waG90byA8LSAgY2EqKGQxM0MuZGlzYy5sZWFmLWErcGhvdG9yZXNwX3Rlcm0pLyhiLWEpXG5gYGBcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
```r
ci.leaf.photo <-  ca*(d13C.disc.leaf-a+photoresp_term)/(b-a)

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->

And iwue to include photorespiration:

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuaXd1ZS5sZWFmLnBob3RvIDwtIChjYS1jaS5sZWFmLnBob3RvKS8xLjZcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
```r
iwue.leaf.photo <- (ca-ci.leaf.photo)/1.6

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

Question 12: Report the rate of ci and describe it in terms of a) proportional   b) similar. Note that this rate translate the ci increase for each ppm/pa of ca increase.

Question 13: Looking at all physiological indices, their trends and rates, how do you interpret the temporal variations of stomatal conductance and photosynthesis of these trees?


With rising ca, variations in plant 13C have been grouped into three leaf gas-exchange strategies:

(1) constant ci, (2) constant ci/ca, and (3) constant ca  ci. 

The first two strategies are considered active, and the third passive. These theoretical considerations serve as the basis for the interpretation of the physiological mechanisms underlying iWUE trends. Recently, a dynamic strategy has been described for low CO2 levels (<400 ppm) where trees switch between the 3 strategies described above.

Calculate ci following scenario 1:

<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuYGBgclxuIyBmaXJzdCwgZXN0aW1hdGUgdGhlIGF2ZXJhZ2UgY2kgZnJvbSB0cmVlIHJpbmcgZm9yIHRoZSBmaXJzdCBkZWNhZGUgb2YgdGhlIHJlY29yZFxuY2kuYXZlcmFnZV8xZGVjYWRlIDwtIG1lYW4oY2kubGVhZi5waG90b1sxOjEwXSlcbmNpLnNjZW5hcmlvMSA8LSB0cyhyZXAoY2kuYXZlcmFnZV8xZGVjYWRlLCAxMDIpLCBzdGFydD0xOTAxLCBmcmVxdWVuY3k9MSlcbmBgYFxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
# first, estimate the average ci from tree ring for the first decade of the record
ci.average_1decade <- mean(ci.leaf.photo[1:10])
